  Advanced Midjourney Settings

In this lesson, we'll take a look at advanced settings inside of Midjourney for speeding up the creative direction process. I'll cover various topics from prompt weighting to seeds. It's kinda nerdy, but really helpful if you want to get the most out of this tool.

Editor's Note: With a recent update you can pull seeds from both the 4-panel images and the upresed single images. This sentence will make more sense after you watch the video. :)

My Recommended Settings for Cinematography

  • Midjourney Version: The Latest Version
  • Style Setting: Low
  • Aspect Ratio: 2:1
  • Remix Mode: Activated

Prompt Codes:

Aspect Ratio: --ar 16:9

  • 2:1 = Cinematic
  • 16:9 = HD

Style: --s 625

  • Pick a number from 0 to 1000
  • 625 is the default style number.
  • Less style = more control
  • More style = more creativity
  • Generally you want more control, so you can even use the 'Raw' mode setting which will set the style to 0.

Subtractive Prompts: --no horse

  • Use this prompt to specify which objects you don't want to see in your scene.
  • List out multiple things by simply placing a space between the words.

Repeat: --r 5

  • Will repeat a prompt up to 40 times.

Quality: --q 3

  • Pick a number up to 5, 1 is default (can do decimals like .25)
  • Increases the quality of the final image.
  • Increases the amount of computing time required to render the image.

Chaos: --chaos 50

  • Pick a number between 0 and 100, 0 is default.
  • Adds random stylization to your scene
  • Can be helpful to add visual elements that you never thought of including.
  • Can be challenging to art direct a scene if chaos is applied. (not generally recommended for filmmaking purposes)

Seed: --seed 828028590

  • Pulls the art direction from a previously rendered image block.
  • Find the seed by applying the ✉️ emoji to a 4-block rendered image or a single upresed image.
  • The seed number will be sent to your inbox.

Prompt Weighting: ::4

  • Pick any number between 0 and 5, Default weight is 1.
  • Adds more or less weight to certain elements of your prompt.
